      <TR BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD colspan="2" width="100%" ALIGN="LEFT">
         <FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana" COLOR="#c0c0c0">
         18.  <b>"OK, one last thing."</b></FONT></TD></TR>
      <TR BGCOLOR="#000000"><td colspan="2" width="100%">
         <FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana" COLOR="#c0c0c0">
         <blockquote>
         Diversity forces people to group up, such that the strategy is on the wider scale, not on the narrow scale. In that sense, Shadowbane is supposed to be about guild v guild warfare, and, like they've been saying all along, /not/ about PvP like everyone else has known it.<P>All I'm saying is, when there are so many possible character combos, it's conceivable that a good many of them will be considered useful, and some could still be more useful overall, while others will be good in moderation (i.e., you get a horde of warrior shock troops, and one or two mages and/or healers for support. Some people really do like to play support, really.)<P>No, I don't expect that creating and re-creating combos will be fun for the first few people, and I'm not looking forward to the changes. BUT, if the game is designed such that LOTS of player types can play LOTS of different characters, then the possibility that one ultra-ass-kicking-gamebreaking PC archetype will not arise -- or, even if it does, nerfing it to the 'standard' level will not affect the majority of gameplay.<P>No, I did not mean to say that PvP is ultimately pointless. I meant to say that it should be a cycle, and that cycle should not exist solely to separate the player base into winners and losers, because such a world cannot survive.<P>J.<BR>damned vulpine<BR><a href="http://sb.xrgaming.net/" target="_blank">http://sb.xrgaming.net/</a>
         </blockquote></FONT></TD></TR>
