         <blockquote>
         I agree with all that Fizz.  I'd add, though, that SB will probably have additional layers of interesting stuff.  "Controlling an Empire" means more than one on one battles and bitchfests...<P>- I think infiltration into enemy guild compounds will have real effects.  That means that those of us who are not into he click-fest will have some fun sneaking around in other peoples castles and doing "quiet work" like (i'm hoping) poisoning's, setting traps, and even the occasional assassination of a guild leader.<P>- Sieges will be (i'm told) grand efforts of organization.  a 72 hour siege needs coordinated personnel who may of may not be PvP gods... at least to stand around the Tebuche for a shift fending off would be defenders at 3am Eastern.<P>- Although there are not a whole lot of trade skills, I'd bet that the "forgemaster" skills are going to be of use to a large guild.  Someone's got to do that stuff.<P>- Maybe most important... whoever is building a large city for their guild has got to determine if its better to put in a Wizard Tower or commit resources to additional NPC guards (or whatever trade-offs come up).  This takes the one on one view of a first person shooter (if you will) and effectively "raises it" to a more "bird's eye" level of (if you'll permit me) a Real Time Strategy game.  Taking real people and useing them as armies in a geographical cntrol context adds several levels and, after you've had enough of one level, you'll want to climb to new levels... thus making the politics of online guild management part of the game rather than a chat channel dictator.<P>... and I'd bet the list goes on.<P>~f
         </blockquote></FONT></TD></TR>
